│ original IR, the select hides this poison by choosing the other arm (-1) for  │
│ the true condition lane. The transformation turns this into an unconditional  │
│ uadd.sat with the same operands, which now observes the poison and propagates │
│ it into the result. Alive2 confirms this: source result is all -1 values      │
│ while target result is poison on one lane. Therefore, the transformation is   │
│ not preserving poison semantics.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug-only   │
│ log shows the first transformation point is foldSelectInstWithICmp which      │
│ calls canonicalizeSaturatedAdd and immediately replaces the select with a     │
│ uadd.sat intrinsic. No other transformations occur before this. The log       │
│ confirms the select was replaced by a call and the compare/add are erased. So │
│ the introduced difference in poison behavior is coming from                   │
│ canonicalizeSaturatedAdd.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe                     │
│ canonicalizeSaturatedAdd matcher uses \"AllowPoison\" variants of matchers    │
│ (m_APIntAllowPoison and m_SpecificIntAllowPoison) to accept constants that    │
│ may be poison. This enables folding patterns where the add operand or         │
│ comparator constant can be partially-poison. While this is acceptable in some │
│ simplifications that preserve conditional semantics, it is not safe when      │
│ replacing a select with an unconditional intrinsic call because the intrinsic │
│ will consume the potentially-poison inputs regardless of the select           │
│ condition. In the reproducer, that is precisely what happens: the false arm   │
│ add uses a partially-poison constant (~C matched with AllowPoison), and the   │
│ select could avoid that poison for some elements. The uadd.sat call does not, │
│ so the target becomes more poisonous than the source.\n\nTherefore, the bug   │
│ is that canonicalizeSaturatedAdd accepts and folds patterns involving poison  │
│ constants via the AllowPoison matchers, breaking poison masking by the        │
│ select.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nWe should make                        │
│ canonicalizeSaturatedAdd conservative by disallowing poison-tolerant matching │
│ in the rules that map the select into a uadd.sat intrinsic. Specifically,     │
│ replace m_APIntAllowPoison and m_SpecificIntAllowPoison with their non-poison │
│ variants. This avoids folding when any of the matched constants could be      │
│ poison, preserving the original select's ability to mask poison               │
│ values.\n\nEdit Point 1 (lines 1009–1016):\n- Change the matching of FVal as  │
│ add with APIntAllowPoison and Cmp1 as SpecificIntAllowPoison to use strict    │
│ m_APInt and m_SpecificInt.\n\nEdit Point 2 (lines 1021–1026):\n- Similarly,   │
│ for the ICMP_UGT case, remove AllowPoison variants.\n\nEdit Point 3 (lines    │
│ 1030–1036):\n- For the ICMP_UGE case, remove AllowPoison variants and use     │
│ strict versions; also keep the !C->isZero() guard.\n\nThese edits ensure that │
│ the fold to uadd.sat is only performed when the constants involved are        │
│ definitely not poison, preventing the semantic change that leads to increased │
│ poison.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy eliminating the use of AllowPoison matchers in  │
│ canonicalizeSaturatedAdd, InstCombine will no longer fold select-based        │
│ saturated add patterns when the constants might be poison. This preserves the │
│ original select's poison-masking behavior and fixes the incorrect             │
│ transformation demonstrated by the reproducer. The expected effect is that    │
│ the problematic case will not be transformed to uadd.sat, maintaining         │
│ equivalence and satisfying Alive2."})                                         │
