│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The transformation in InstCombine replaces a select-based saturated add       │
│ pattern with a call to llvm.uadd.sat. In the provided reproducer, one lane of │
│ a vector operand is poison due to a partially-poison constant used in an xor  │
│ ("<i32 -1, i32 poison>"). In the original IR, the select hides this poison by │
│ choosing the other arm (-1) for the true condition lane. The transformation   │
│ turns this into an unconditional uadd.sat with the same operands, which now   │
│ observes the poison and propagates it into the result. Alive2 confirms this:  │
│ source result is all -1 values while target result is poison on one lane.     │
│ Therefore, the transformation is not preserving poison semantics.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug-only log shows the first transformation point is                    │
│ foldSelectInstWithICmp which calls canonicalizeSaturatedAdd and immediately   │
│ replaces the select with a uadd.sat intrinsic. No other transformations occur │
│ before this. The log confirms the select was replaced by a call and the       │
│ compare/add are erased. So the introduced difference in poison behavior is    │
│ coming from canonicalizeSaturatedAdd.                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The canonicalizeSaturatedAdd matcher uses "AllowPoison" variants of matchers  │
│ (m_APIntAllowPoison and m_SpecificIntAllowPoison) to accept constants that    │
│ may be poison. This enables folding patterns where the add operand or         │
│ comparator constant can be partially-poison. While this is acceptable in some │
│ simplifications that preserve conditional semantics, it is not safe when      │
│ replacing a select with an unconditional intrinsic call because the intrinsic │
│ will consume the potentially-poison inputs regardless of the select           │
│ condition. In the reproducer, that is precisely what happens: the false arm   │
│ add uses a partially-poison constant (~C matched with AllowPoison), and the   │
│ select could avoid that poison for some elements. The uadd.sat call does not, │
│ so the target becomes more poisonous than the source.                         │
│                                                                               │
│ Therefore, the bug is that canonicalizeSaturatedAdd accepts and folds         │
│ patterns involving poison constants via the AllowPoison matchers, breaking    │
│ poison masking by the select.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points(s):                                                   │
│ We should make canonicalizeSaturatedAdd conservative by disallowing           │
│ poison-tolerant matching in the rules that map the select into a uadd.sat     │
│ intrinsic. Specifically, replace m_APIntAllowPoison and                       │
│ m_SpecificIntAllowPoison with their non-poison variants. This avoids folding  │
│ when any of the matched constants could be poison, preserving the original    │
│ select's ability to mask poison values.                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit Point 1 (lines 1009–1016):                                               │
│ - Change the matching of FVal as add with APIntAllowPoison and Cmp1 as        │
│ SpecificIntAllowPoison to use strict m_APInt and m_SpecificInt.               │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit Point 2 (lines 1021–1026):                                               │
│ - Similarly, for the ICMP_UGT case, remove AllowPoison variants.              │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit Point 3 (lines 1030–1036):                                               │
│ - For the ICMP_UGE case, remove AllowPoison variants and use strict versions; │
│ also keep the !C->isZero() guard.                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ These edits ensure that the fold to uadd.sat is only performed when the       │
│ constants involved are definitely not poison, preventing the semantic change  │
│ that leads to increased poison.                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By eliminating the use of AllowPoison matchers in canonicalizeSaturatedAdd,   │
│ InstCombine will no longer fold select-based saturated add patterns when the  │
│ constants might be poison. This preserves the original select's               │
│ poison-masking behavior and fixes the incorrect transformation demonstrated   │
│ by the reproducer. The expected effect is that the problematic case will not  │
│ be transformed to uadd.sat, maintaining equivalence and satisfying Alive2.    │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
